20px; height: 149px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e6b7d8c3-58b8-45cc-9af5-8ea9bf1fd6dd-image.png\" style=\"width: 157px; height: 278px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/829aa742-e745-4714-84aa-a9b8575a7924-image.png\" style=\"width: 223px; height: 93px;\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e9a41cc1-23f7-4ad3-bf49-6966ec7ebbfa-image.png\" style=\"width: 553px; height: 185px;\" /><br />7 member cyclic anhydide is less stable.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27642,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/17ad82ca-bd77-4f67-b340-21c05457c7d3-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b142730-f0be-4ce4-b152-aabc79f5e36b-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 110px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc3ad91c-69bf-40d9-876b-adbcf5b5e5ea-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 80px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a8d5d272-10a3-43c0-bea7-a0ebe1f758d4-image.png\" style=\"width: 158px; height: 80px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>First heterolytic&nbsp;fission of iodine will take place and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;will attack at double bond site. Then oxygen of carboxylic acid will attack on the carbocation, forming a cyclic ring. In last step elimination reaction will take place in presence of heat and Py.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa35534c-b562-42c1-9744-d03fbbf1575d-image.png\" style=\"width: 526px; height: 250px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27659,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a7930ea2-f814-4b77-803f-4abce551f69b-image.png\" style=\"width: 59px; height: 71px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f582ffd8-fea7-4e42-8816-8030a8026161-image.png\" style=\"width: 49px; height: 73px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81621cd7-fc1a-48f6-895a-1ceb8f175d8a-image.png\" style=\"width: 103px; height: 72px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/40074224-16d2-4840-b2b1-b082932ef1df-image.png\" style=\"width: 82px; height: 71px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/018500cf-7770-4785-9200-fbc75c9b983e-74c6beee-d093-4df9-8aa0-478e921005b2-image.png\" style=\"width: 319px; height: 147px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27646,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect.","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/533cd67d-8466-431e-a414-47d83de159ce-image.png\" style=\"width: 512px; height: 300px;\" /></p><p>In the above reaction&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;group&nbsp;is replaced by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OR</mi></math>&nbsp;group. Hence, nucleophilic substitution reaction is involved. Electron withdrawing groups increases the stability of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, hence, rate of reaction increases.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27627,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["\\(r  \\gt  q  \\gt  p  \\gt  s\\)","\\(q  \\gt  p  \\gt  r  \\gt  s\\)","\\(p  \\gt  r  \\gt  q  \\gt  s\\)","\\(p  \\gt  q  \\gt  r  \\gt  s\\)"],"answer":3,"solution":"Rate of hydrolysis \\(\\propto\\) Leaving group ability<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1fmgXuI01qyQTleHhIzYYCAOUoLmDcmqd4xTgttT1pY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27625,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["D","A","B","C"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/O_8Io7VV57ec8Mhu_ZEhR2PDOMMFJIVMD-assmasFTQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />C.B. of terminal alkyne will be sp hybridisation and loculised. In other C.B. will be resonance stablised.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27640,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>When salicylic acid is heated with methyl alcohol, the carboxyl group of salicylic acid is esterified producing a strong-smelling liquid ester (methyl salicylate). Aspirin is prepared by chemical synthesis from salicylic acid, through acetylation with acetic anhydride.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/671e3d54-d3fa-47ae-8761-34b1efb27a37-9896850_1.PNG\" style=\"width: 602px; height: 150px;\" />&nbsp;Hence, reagent&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#39;</mo></math>&nbsp;respectively are:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>CO</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27667,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efde76c4-7004-456c-bfce-cb18582c0d04-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 180px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2daa01ac-d9f7-4bf9-a0e1-5a5eac225898-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 183px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9e7cbecb-8060-400e-a4ff-aea82c71e724-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 180px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/849f3c77-4a7e-4f2b-aaa6-6e61e4304399-image.png\" style=\"width: 260px; height: 187px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1541dfbe-bcb2-4a7c-bd27-dc2e3c180a98-image.png\" style=\"width: 650px; height: 271px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27647,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>63</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>90</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>104</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>142</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f0ff0b80-bcb0-4fab-a066-6d3a09d469a4-image.png\" style=\"width: 800px; height: 90px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1da264d8-5cf1-48df-999e-258094014a22-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 209px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c8af080a-a5ba-430a-b3fa-e182e19e2d23-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 75px;\" />C is a para isomer.</p><p>The melting point of para-isomer is comparatively&nbsp;higher than the corresponding&nbsp; ortho and meta-isomers , because of more&nbsp;symmetrical nature; it&nbsp;fits into crystal lattice more readily&nbsp;and so, close packing of molecules in crystal lattice increases the intermolecular force of attraction between molecules.</p><p>Hence&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;has highest melting point that is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>142</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27648,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>LiAlH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>MnO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NaBH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>When benzoic acid is heated with formic acid in presence of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Mno</mi></math>, benzaldehyde is obtained.</p><p>The reaction is given below, along with benzaldehyde, carbondioxide and water are also obtained.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>HCOOH</mi><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Heat</mi><mi>MnO</mi></munderover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>CHO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27628,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$6$","$3$","$5$","$4$"],"answer":2,"solution":"The compounds having benzylic hydrogen will give benzoic acid on treatment with hot KMnO 4 .\nWhich are following:\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/giRRYQZYGv46-yd_KvyYqpocq4YJwsxi5pXLFwa1Kds.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27681,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71c6330d-31e4-4fdc-8ffa-a9a085be0624-image.png\" style=\"width: 122px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/64e71f11-9d15-486e-a8b5-e0f7fa9c3a5a-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/adbeb9f2-d1b3-409c-9e75-3953380b66b8-image.png\" style=\"width: 121px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/33e701db-30f2-4d96-81de-505b434c4ac0-image.png\" style=\"width: 110px; height: 135px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/448bb025-0c1c-47f1-8abf-c266f31a6e64-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 124px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":27694,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COCl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CHCOOH}$","$\\mathrm{ClCH}_2 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RnKOv31ZXIAr5RihYMyaBE3hQ_f5se7UqkY3V62OVnE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":27649,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect.","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The melting point of carboxylic acid has no trend as we can observe from the following data of metling point.</p><p>Methanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Ethanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Propanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Butanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Pentonoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>35</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Hexonic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Heptanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, Octanoic acid <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math> acid. Water solubility of carboxylic acid decreases as we increase the molar mass &amp; hence hydrophobic part of the chain.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27689,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{PhCOOH}$","$\\mathrm{O}-\\mathrm{NO}_2 \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_4 \\mathrm{COOH}$","$\\mathrm{p}-\\mathrm{NO}_2 \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_4 \\mathrm{COOH}$","$\\mathrm{m}-\\mathrm{NO}_2 \\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_4 \\mathrm{COOH}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27644,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/668ce3ce-2388-4c15-9278-b1d11b49d774-image.png\" style=\"width: 288px; height: 100px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8e8e7a64-b2dd-44c8-8317-2f3b163963a5-image.png\" style=\"width: 215px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>CHBr</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3224c753-b644-4cf5-ad0b-a9b19eb2ee34-image.png\" style=\"width: 84px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a6646ac4-6585-4b91-b897-613471f0e720-image.png\" style=\"width: 85px; height: 120px;\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>CHBr</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Based on the percentage composition of the elements given the molecular formula of the compound is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>9</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi></math></p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc1671c4-65f6-42ef-9f4b-924a0c4a6842-dbe.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 156px;\" /></p><p>And the degree of unsaturation or double bond equivalent of&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>9</mn></msub><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;is 4.</p><p>It is mentioned that A is optically active and gives pale yellow precipitate with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p><p>Hence, the structures of A and B can be deduced based on the following reactions.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cfc77f5-782b-4944-9836-8f18e2d22e25-13-7-20223.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 378px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27653,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Carboxylic Acid Derivatives","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b487b52-6128-48ab-902c-062b8b7e310e-image.png\" style=\"width: 325px; height: 132px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8094e1cf-8b9e-4030-b496-5095b35bc001-image.png\" style=\"width: 325px; height: 132px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9f8312d8-a1bf-42d6-97ee-e8bce0112cc9-image.png\" style=\"width: 308px; height: 132px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2faa9938-925f-40ee-869a-8485e17b09cd-image.png\" style=\"width: 362px; height: 132px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f050d57a-e0e1-4f4f-ad39-0053d184d0af-image.png\" style=\"width: 869px; height: 323px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null}]